values:
Vincent x Gabriel. You've been warned. First person Vincent. Not really great at this but hey it's something.<br /><br /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="CONTENT-TYPE" /><title></title><meta content="OpenOffice.org 3.0  (Win32)" name="GENERATOR" /><style type="text/css">
	<!--
		@page { margin: 0.79in }
		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }
	-->
	</style> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><lj-cut text="dot dot dot"><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif">Another night, another argument. I can't count how many times we've had this &ldquo;discussion&rdquo; and I'm certain neither of us are willing to concede defeat any time soon. I could hear his footsteps getting closer together as he paced in front of me.</font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif">I don't know how you can be so stubborn, I really don't. How many more times do I need to tell you that I'm fine with this?&rdquo;</font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif">You're really starting to irritate me,&rdquo; I shot back, deflecting his statement with it. Hell, it was the truth so what did it matter if I was deflecting? </font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif">Make that two of us, then. <i>You've</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> been irritating me for the past few weeks. You think I enjoy watching you be a masochist when I've got just the thing to make you feel better?&rdquo; </span></font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Gabriel just didn't understand, and until he started having cravings for chewing on my neck I doubt he ever would. Oh it was tempting alright, and every time we argued it just got worse. How easy would it be to say yes? Gabe was offering it up like it didn't mean anything and </span><i>that</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> was probably what had me so upset. Didn't he know the danger he was putting himself in? Did he care?</span></font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">No, Gabe.&rdquo; It was my final word on the matter.</span></font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">But when did Gabriel ever let that stop him?</span></font><br /><br /> <br /></span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><span style="font-size: small;"><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">I've had it with you and your self imposed punishment. It doesn't matter how much normal blood you drink you're always going to need some of mine from now on. I've accepted that, why can't you do the same?&rdquo;</span></font></p> </span><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Because you have </span><i>no idea</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> how it makes me feel and you </span><i>never</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> will. So why don't you just drop it, I'm not drinking from you and I can tell when you try and mix it in with my supply. I'd really rather not waste another batch because you've decided to go on some fool's mission to make me want to do things your way.&rdquo; I really wasn't going to have any of it but Gabriel had to go and do something extremely misguided and foolish. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">I smelled the blood the instant the wound hit air and every particle of my being ached to taste it. He knew I hadn't had any wolf's blood in weeks. He </span><i>knew</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> it. I was at a loss whether to just leave the room or strangle him for being so reckless but I could do neither as I sat in silence while the couch shifted to accept the weight of the foolhardy wolf. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Gabriel...&rdquo; to my own ears that sounded like a plea and though my pride stung I could only hope Gabe heard the same. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Stop fighting me on this, I know I'm right. You just need to trust me.&rdquo; </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">The smell was stronger than ever and I knew Gabe was holding his wrist close to my face. My arms felt sluggish yet I couldn't stop their rise to clutch onto his arm and draw the slight wound to my lips. Just a taste nearly sent my mind reeling off the edge. I felt my body shudder and in that moment all I knew was that I wanted more. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">The thing about wolf's blood is that once you have a taste you can hardly stop yourself from getting more. I lunged for Gabriel's neck but thankfully I had enough sense of self to spare him any violence on my part. His head hit the pillow at the other end of the couch and I was on top of him, fangs burying quickly and efficiently into his neck to draw out twin wells of blood. Life giving blood. Energy coursed through my veins as the warm and thick substance absorbed into my body teetering on the ledge between living and dead. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">He clutched at my arm and I sucked harder, determining to get my fill and be done with it. With a force of will I brought my head up and licked at the two punctures until they closed. Too late for Gabriel now to back out of this, he'd open the flood gates and I wasn't even sure I could stop even if I tried. So much for that shirt too, my fingers clawed it right off his body. And where those moans I heard in pleasure or pain? I hadn't meant to catch skin with my nails. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Gabriel must have sensed my hesitation. &ldquo;Don't stop now...I...I really don't mind.&rdquo; </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Was I hearing him right? He didn't </span><i>mind</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> a little abuse? This was a slippery slope I was standing on. On the one hand it was hot to hear Gabe moan like that from just a few scratches but on the other if he enjoyed it too much I could honestly hurt Gabriel and that was never something I wanted to let myself do. Then again, Gabriel wasn't some hapless human who didn't know what he was getting himself involved with. If push came to shove the wolf was more than capable of defending himself until one of them could come to their senses. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">My tongue found its way to those scrapes and pressed hard as it licked up whatever coppery tasting blood it could find. Both of my hands were pinning Gabriel's arms back almost as if they had a will of their own, and the wolf's moans only fanned the flames. So the little potter liked to be held down? This was new, but somehow not all that surprising to me. I could certainly work with it in the mood that I was in. A little shifting brought the fact of just how much of a mood to my attention...and to Gabriel's. Nothing like a month of abstinence to make me just a little trigger happy. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Even in my heated state I knew the couch wasn't going to be the best location for what I wanted to do next with Gabe. &ldquo;Up,&rdquo; I commanded simply, doing the same to get off the couch. I could feel Gabriel moving along beside me but we never made it to the bedroom. Just inside the hallway I had him pinned to the wall, my hungry lips on his pressing our mouths together in a fierce embrace. Each hand found their counterpart's wrist on Gabriel and held them to the wall above his head. I was hungry, but this time not for blood. When I shifted my hips to his I could feel that I wasn't alone. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Haa...&rdquo; we hissed in unison. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">You're a lot kinkier than I imagined,&rdquo; I breathed into one ear, my lips next moving to the wolf's neck as I was so fond of doing. I knew how much it got to him. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;">&ldquo;<font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Heh...nngh...the things you find out when you quit arguing with me.&rdquo; </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">Well, he had a point and I wasn't about to take the time to argue with him about it. Not right now at least. &ldquo;Yeah, I'll try and keep that in mind,&rdquo; my voice strained into an ear. If normal blood made me antsy wolf blood made me downright voracious. My darker elements were boiling, a reason I hate feeding from Gabe. How could someone so damn </span><i>good</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> turn me into someone so damn </span><i>evil</i><span style="font-style: normal;">? Well perhaps not evil, but I felt damn close. </span></font> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><span style="font-size: small;"><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><i>That little wolf had asked for it</i><span style="font-style: normal;">. My hands switched positions up a little, transferring one wrist to the other so that it could dive freely down and go for the latches of Gabe's pants. No time for romance, I'm on the clock and I'll be damned if I lose an opportunity. Our tune changed with my body pressing up to his and I could notice the distinct discomfort of cloth between skin. Gabe wasn't going anywhere so my hands changed direction and started on my own shirt, prying apart the damnable buttons one by one until I could completely shrug it off. Silk didn't belong on the floor but there it would stay followed by my slacks for the remainder of the night.</span></font></p> </span><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><br /> </span></p><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-size: small;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><span style="font-style: normal;">There weren't any words, I simply pushed myself to him and let my hungry lips do all the talking in silence. Well, </span><i>relative </i><span style="font-style: normal;">silence. Gabriel made enough noise for the both of us when skin met skin. I'm sure the wall wasn't entirely comfortable but Gabriel wasn't complaining. </span></font> </span></p></lj-cut><br /><br />

Been a while but I'm back at it, somewhat. I'm on vacation at the moment but I&nbsp;had a muse and Jack had class so the result was some writing. I'm not completely satisfied with it but then again I'm never completely satisfied with most that I&nbsp;do. <br /><br />Warning: STAR&nbsp;TREK. Has NOTHING to do with the new movie, which by the way was fuckin' spectacular and awesome and I&nbsp;loved it. <br /><br />For any fans who'd like to know this is set in 2367 at the battle of Wolf 359. And don't tell me that the massacre left no one but the Enterprise alive because that means you've never seen Deep Space 9. Hello, Sisko and&nbsp;Jake? Not to mention everyone else who managed to get into escape pods and make it out alive. Sorry, but some twit who thinks he knows it all told me no one else survived this battle and he's just dead WRONG. I like being right. Feels great.<br /><br /><br /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="CONTENT-TYPE" /><title></title><meta content="OpenOffice.org 3.0  (Win32)" name="GENERATOR" /><style type="text/css">
	<!--
		@page { margin: 0.79in }
		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }
	-->
	</style> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i>Engineering!</i><span style="font-style: normal;">&rdquo; the captain's voice pierced the thick air of main engineering over the bustling officers scurrying about like ants trying to repair their hopelessly damaged hill. &ldquo;</span><i>Status report,</i><span style="font-style: normal;">&rdquo; he demanded. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><lj-cut text="Red Alert..."><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><i>If I had anything new to tell you I would have already</i><span style="font-style: normal;">, Lieutenant Narib thought to himself but slapped his right hand to his left shoulder to respond all the same. His voice was considerably less aggravated than his thoughts, though his stress echoed through every syllable. &ldquo;I'm losing the electromagnetic stability of the warp core's magnetic field, the generators just don't have enough reserve power to maintain the shields and the core's field, Captain. At the rate it's falling we'll need to evacuate the ship in fifteen minutes.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i>Unacceptable, the Borg cube is already powering up for warp and the Enterprise can't take it alone. I need those engines operational</i><span style="font-style: normal;">.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><i>Operational?</i><span style="font-style: normal;"> Narib's mind spat the word like a curse, </span><i>the damn engines are barely <b>functional</b><span style="font-weight: normal;"> much less operational.</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;"> &ldquo;I understand that but if we lose containment it won't be a matter of getting the engines operational, it'll be a matter of getting the core ejected.&rdquo; Come to think of it he wasn't even sure if it was possible to eject the core now that they'd sustained further damage from the escaping Borg cube. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">With the comlink still engaged Narib could hear the sigh and the subsequent defeat in his captain's voice. &ldquo;</span></span><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Power down the engines and fix that damn field</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">.&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">I could have told you that in the first place</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">, Narib muttered internally with a scowl to the main control panel in front of him. Trained eyes scanned over the multicolored LCAR display tracing the flow speed of both the matter and antimatter streams into the warp core. Tapping the control pad he brought up the command prompts to shut the core down but was halted by the angry sounding error bleep. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The lieutenant's eyes widened as he read the display readouts and before he could do anything else his hand was slapping at the badge on his left shoulder. &ldquo;Captain! We need to eject the core </span></span><span style="font-style: normal;"><b>now</b></span><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">!&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Engineering? What's going on?</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">I don't have time for this!</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;"> &ldquo;Captain the magnetic constrictors were damaged, they're injecting the core with matter and antimatter too quickly for the containment fields to keep up with, we're looking at a complete warp core breach in under fiver minutes and I can't shut it down.&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><b>Warning, warp core breach imminent.</b></span><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo; The computer's unnervingly calm voice announced right on cue. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">An eerie red glow lit up the right side of the Bajoran's face in a rhythmic fashion from the panel running alongside the wall displaying the status of Red Alert. For a handful of heartbeats he waited for the captain to make up his mind, a struggle that seemed to be consuming his commanding officer ever since they entered the Wolf system and the battle raging there. Fingers raced over the control panel in an effort to at least stem the flow of the twin fuel sources that were gushing into the core and hurling the Galaxy class starship into very treacherous waters. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Eject the core, Lieutenant,</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo; he could hear the com system switch over to full broadcast, &ldquo;</span></span><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">this is the captain speaking, all hands brace for impact and prepare to evacuate.</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo; Again the com switched, this time back over to the lieutenant's channel. &ldquo;</span></span><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Prepare to divert all power to the shields, Lieutenant, I doubt we'll escape the blast radi--</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Captain, I can't activate the ejection sequence,&rdquo; Narib interrupted with the discouraging news, &ldquo;the system is too badly damaged.&rdquo; For a long moment the engineer stared at the angrily flashing warning on the display panel in front of him, listening to the rhythmic blaring of alarms and the calm warning that their ship was about to blow itself to pieces. His mind, however, was far from idle. Every mechanical spec of the ship were running through his mind as fast as he could recall them, searching for some way to stall the inevitable if only for long enough to get most of the crew to the escape pods. His captain was already ahead of him in that regard.</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">--and meet at the rendezvous point. I repeat, all hands to the escape pods, scatter yourselves and meet at the rendezvous point.</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The forward chamber holding the warp core was all but blocked from view by vented gas and the computer once again chimed in to warn them of the theta radiation danger they faced, not to mention the impending explosion once the field dropped to below fifteen percent. It was a short jog over to the blast door control panel, his voice carried as far as he could project it ordering all of his engineering staff out and to their escape pods located in the adjacent corridor. A smudged faced crewman paused to acknowledge he was the last one out. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Lieutenant?&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Go on, I'm going to buy us some time. I'll be right behind you.&rdquo; The Bajoran could see he wasn't convincing the younger officer who then looked reluctant to leave. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">You won't last in there, sir. Not alone, anyway. What's the plan?&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Narib's brows furrowed above an equally crinkled nose but the crewman was right he couldn't do this alone. &ldquo;We'll siphon off the containment field from the storage pods, it won't last but it'll at least buy us enough time to get those pods out of range.&rdquo; His crewman nodded.</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The pair of them entered the sweltering warp core chamber and he could immediately feel the effects of intense theta radiation. His crewman cocked his head to the side as they split out around the core. &ldquo;You do know this is entirely against Starfleet regulations, right?&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The lieutenant had to give a lopsided smile at that before his fingers raced over the control panel. &ldquo;I'll let them lecture me on it later. Be prepared to drain your pod's containment field on my mark, this has to be done simultaneously for it to work.&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><b>Warning, warp core breach imminent. Theta radiation levels approaching fatal limits.</b></span><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">A shaking hand reached up to brush aside sweat from his brow in mild irritation as radiation sickness started to set in. &ldquo;Computer,&rdquo; Narib barked, &ldquo;shut that damn thing off!&rdquo; He didn't need to be reminded of the danger they were in, it was painfully obvious enough. &ldquo;Yvers, isn't it?&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Yes sir. Brandon sir.&rdquo; The pair of them exchanged glances before cutting their eyes away to their respective control panels. No time to get better acquainted.</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Decrease containment at five percent increments starting at my mark and every two seconds after that until you reach twenty five percent capacity. That should hold both the core and the pods for ten minutes at the most.&rdquo; He was being overly optimistic but at a time like this they could use some optimism. &ldquo;Mark.&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Dialing back the antimatter containment fields around their storage pods was against regulations for a reason and it was a damn good one too. If the antimatter contained inside touched the canister itself the blast from the energy released during complete annihilation of both particles would be catastrophic. The storage pods themselves were designed with separate containment fields and generators for those fields as a precaution if the ship were to be destroyed the antimatter would be safely contained. To tamper with the fields was no small offense on a starship, however when that ship was facing a warp core breach suddenly the regulations didn't seem so absolute. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">A fluctuation in the twin pod's magnetic containment field caught his attention and when he looked over he saw Crewman Yvers gripping the panel in front of him as if it were the only thing keeping him standing. &ldquo;Yvers! Don't fall behind, this has to be simultaneous or we'll blow the ship right now.&rdquo; He could understand how the man felt, however, with his own vision starting to swirl the control's colors together into shimmering patterns. Hallucinations were just the start of radiation sickness, but at the rate they were being exposed it was the least of their worries. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Y-yes sir! Sorry sir, I don't know what came over me.&rdquo; Yvers blinked the fuzzy vision out of his own eyes and keyed in the right sequence to match his containment field's strength with Lieutenant Narib's. &ldquo;You know, sir, it's been an honor. You weren't anything like I was expecting.&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Good, keep him talking</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">. &ldquo;Oh? And what was that?&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">I dunno, more of a tight ass like the professors at the academy.&rdquo; Immediately Yvers stiffened and looked like he'd been caught out of uniform on the job. &ldquo;I'm sorry sir, that was inappropriate.&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Vadi smiled as he punched in the next round of instructions to the panel. &ldquo;Brandon, we're soaked in sweat and theta radiation, as long as you keep decreasing that field I don't give a damn what kind of language you use. Hell, I'm about to get pretty colorful myself.&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Brandon chuckled and punched in the orders to decrease field strength on cue. &ldquo;I thought the Bajoran prophets frowned on that sort of thing, if you don't mind my curiosity.&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">They probably do, but they aren't here and they'll have to get in line with Starfleet and take it up with me later.&rdquo; </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Yeah, if we make it out of here,&rdquo; Brandon muttered, looking as if he was about to lose his footing again. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">We will. This is going to work, we've already boosted the internal warp core field by ten percent.&rdquo; It wasn't much and it certainly wasn't enough to save the ship but it was more than enough to keep it from breaching just yet. &ldquo;We're almost at twenty five percent storage pod capacity, be prepared to get the hell out of here once we reach it.&rdquo; </span></span><i><span style="font-weight: normal;">I have no idea how long it'll hold</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">, Narib thought to himself, there was no need to verbalize what they both were thinking. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Engineering?</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The voice was disembodied and startling enough that the lieutenant forgot to hit his combadge to respond at first. &ldquo;Captain?&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">The hell are you doing on this ship still? I'm getting fluctuating readings from engineering, is that you?</span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">&rdquo;</span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Yes sir, I've stabilized the warp core's containment field but it won't hold for much longer and it's going to take the antimatter storage pods with it.&rdquo; He didn't need to ask why the captain was still on the ship. It was an old Earth custom he had read about in one of his various data books on old Earth sailing technology. Captains tended to go down with their ships and just because the venue had changed didn't mean the mindset followed course. </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<i><span style="font-weight: normal;">Good job, but get the hell out of there. You've done enough.&rdquo; </span></i><span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;"> </span></span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;<span style="font-style: normal;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">On my way out already, sir. And...&rdquo; it was against protocol but he'd say it anyway, &ldquo;you should be too.&rdquo; </span></span></p></lj-cut><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <br />

Totally going out of order because a muse struck and this one fit. I&nbsp;really do need to get started on these though. <br /><br /><meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8" http-equiv="CONTENT-TYPE" /><title></title><meta content="OpenOffice.org 3.0  (Win32)" name="GENERATOR" /><style type="text/css">
	<!--
		@page { margin: 0.79in }
		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }
	--
</style>   <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><lj-cut><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">Interrogations generally consisted of a few well placed threats to get the creature's attention, deliberate application of pain, and the worthless tongues would loosen in an instant. Generally this was the case and every fresh member could pry what information he needed from the mouths of the damned before ending their miserable 'lives'. When the usual methods proved inadequate for a particularly stubborn creature there were those who were called in to handle the situation. There were those who were trained in various methods of retrieving valuable information from those unwilling to produce it without force.</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">Lycans tended to be the easiest to exploit, Vincent had found. When he had gotten the call he had begun mentally preparing himself for how he would deal with their current uncooperative captive. It was the mark of a good interrogator to keep all of his cards close to his chest and Vincent's poker face was outstanding. His statuesque features remained chiseled as he entered the small room with the chained beast sitting bound to a metallic chair fused into the ground. No doubt he would appear human but Vincent wasn't burdened with facetious appearances.</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;The location,&rdquo; Vincent snapped in a tone that would leave a listener sure of his impatience. His 'routine' was always straightforward, akin to almost everything else he did in life and work.</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;I've already said my peace,&rdquo; came the surprisingly calm reply, &ldquo;you can go ahead and kill me, I won't betray my pack.&rdquo;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&ldquo;It was never a question of our ability to exterminate you,&rdquo; Vincent's coolly modulated voice came back, &ldquo;only a question of <i>when</i><span style="font-style: normal;">.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;Your associates have already done their worst and haven't been able to get very far, which is presumably why you are standing here. Time will do nothing but be wasted.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;There is something you will come to understand,&rdquo; Vincent began with a slight curl taking to his lips, &ldquo;I am not my associates and I was called in because I know how to make creatures like you talk. </span><i>Bring her in</i><span style="font-style: normal;">.&rdquo; The last was spoken toward the door which opened upon his command producing a small child. Judging by the rattled gasp in front of him, Vincent assumed the point had been made. &ldquo;I find that with you Lycans a family member can loosen the tongue, how fortunate for me that you have quite a few.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;</span><i>Daddy!</i><span style="font-style: normal;">&rdquo; her voice squeaked at his side when a hand reached out to grab her by the throat to hold her out standing in front of him. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;Marisa! You can't possibly be capable of killing a </span><i>child</i><span style="font-style: normal;">. She's a harmless natural bred, she doesn't even lose control under the full moon!&rdquo; His voice was no longer that infuriating calm.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;You have absolutely no idea what I am capable of but you are soon to find out if you do not answer my very simple question. I am emphatically uninterested in your lies.&rdquo; To demonstrate just how uninterested he was a hand produced from his side a very slender and very silver jagged blade. The child beast shrieked.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;No! Leave her out of this, she's only a child!&rdquo; The sounds of chains rattling indicated to Vincent the struggle the beast was putting forth to try and get at his young. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	And there it was, that strange twisting in his gut he always felt during operations like this. The feeling was a useless gesture and only served to call into question absolute truths that were unassailable by mere soldiers in this holy war. Pity was a luxury he was not allowed to pursue and it was a weakness he was wholly ashamed of. Nothing of any emotional value registered on his marble visage, and just like the stone he was impervious to the tears around him. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;There is no question as to both of your deaths, the only thing you are in control of in this matter is how fast she dies. I will not ask you again for the location, the next time this blade touches her skin her screams will not stop until I have exactly what I want from you.&rdquo; When the silence extended, broken only by their mutual sobs, his knife hand got to work on the child beast's flesh. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	Five minutes was a veritable eternity with the small child screaming over and over again from the pure agony he was inflicting on her. Her father's responses were only screamed pleas for him to stop, nothing even close to the adequate response to stay his hand. What a stubborn beast. To let your own flesh and blood writhe in pain to keep a secret was so very inhuman, it only served to bolster his confidence that what he was doing couldn't be wrong if they were simply creatures to be dealt with. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	Finally the girl's body began to grow limp in his hands and he knew her usefulness was just about worn out. She had partially changed from the pain and confusion but it was still only a simple matter to reach up to both sides of her head and twist hard until he felt the snap. She was by no means dead, simply immobilized for the moment, but the sharp blade that pierced her heart next quickly ended her life. It was a small mercy at that point.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;</span><i>You're a monster</i><span style="font-style: normal;">,&rdquo; the creature's voice was hoarse from his screams. &ldquo;You dare call us the beasts but you had no problem killing an innocent child.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;She was never innocent,&rdquo; Vincent shot back in a cool clip of his voice, &ldquo;and neither are you. A few simple words could have ended her suffering far sooner.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	An unexpected sound had Vincent tilting his head slightly. A coarse laugh. &ldquo;You've used up your leverage, Hunter. All you can do is kill me now.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	It was Vincent's turn to laugh. &ldquo;Why do you assume that she was the only other one we caught? I plan on destroying every member of your family before you until you give me exactly what I've asked for. We have ways to gently put your kind down, your children could die quietly in their sleep or they could die just like your Marisa--&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;Don't you dare say her name,&rdquo; the command wasn't yelled but instead growled. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;You are not in any kind of position to give me orders, </span><i>Lycan</i><span style="font-style: normal;">. </span><i>Send the wife in next</i><span style="font-style: normal;">.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	There was the sound of a door opening and then a startled gasp filled with horrified grief. The body of the little beast child still laid at his feet. &ldquo;Maybe she will talk if you won't.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;David what...what has he done? What has he done to Marisa?&rdquo; her voice was bordering on panic. Perhaps she would be more useful to him than the husband.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;Lily, don't.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;Your mate has been very uncooperative, the result of which ended in your spawn's rather obnoxiously loud death. It's fortunate that your kind reproduce in droves, I can continue with their extermination until you tell me where your pack leader is.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	Perhaps he should not have been so callous with the female, her only response was a heaving sob for the most part. Odd how they could mimic human emotions so well yet not be worthy of the status of the ones they imitated. &ldquo;Do I need to do another demonstration with your second youngest?&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;We would all rather die than betray our own,&rdquo; the female beast spoke up with an infuriating amount of defiance in her voice that didn't belong there. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	Vincent had many weakness and she had just exploited one of them. Anger was not an emotion he should be having during an operation like this, it only served to get rid of subjects and leverage faster than information could flow. Being defied by a beast was more than he was willing to stomach and his hand impacted her face with ease despite his blindness. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;You are going to regret using that tongue for something other than giving me the information I want. And you,&rdquo; he was directing his voice back at the male, &ldquo;you will be begging for me to listen to you tell me all that I want to know by the time I'm done.&rdquo; </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	With her hands tied and bound behind her back the female was not a threat to him. Turning on them both he strode purposefully to the back of the small interrogations room to bench covered in utensils. The heat coming from one of them guided his hands over. The large crucible was easily held between tongs and the contents remained unspilt as he made his way back over, grabbing the female creature by her hair to lift her sagging body up off the ground. &ldquo;You have exactly one last chance to speak,&rdquo; Vincent hissed out, lifting the crucible up as a warning.</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	&ldquo;</span><i>Go to hell</i><span style="font-style: normal;">.&rdquo;</span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	He wouldn't even dignify that with a verbal response. The hand that had been in her hair swiftly struck out to her jaw, clamping down with enough force to pry her mouth wide open. Without blinking, without even a flicker of emotion in his sightless eyes, he tilted the crucible to pour the molten silver down into her mouth to clog and burn clear down her throat. Her body bucked and the smell that came from her sick gasps was acrid but Vincent still did not flinch. When he finally released her he could hear her thrashing on the ground even over the agonized cry of rage and grief coming from her mate just a foot away. </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p align="center" style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">***</span></p> <p align="left" style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><span style="font-style: normal;">	Vincent woke up in a cold sweat, the ghosts of screams still echoing in his memory. Rolling out of bed he did his best to not wake Gabe across the hall as he stumbled his way into the shared bathroom to empty the contents of the previous night's meal from his gut. Turning on the hot water he cupped the  running liquid from the sink in his hands and splashed it a few times over his face. He was acutely aware of his hands as he placed them under the scalding hot water. Not even the distraction of the water could keep the rebounding question out of his mind. </span><i>What have I done</i><span style="font-style: normal;">? </span></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p> </lj-cut><br />

Ugh. I'm sick and on cold medication so this will suck but that's okay. I've made my peace with the fact that some parts of this novel are going to suck while other parts will be much better. 1205 words. Not bad for not being able to think straight.<br /><meta http-equiv="CONTENT-TYPE" content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><meta name="GENERATOR" content="OpenOffice.org 2.2  (Win32)"><meta name="AUTHOR" content="Brian Confer"><meta name="CREATED" content="20081101;8524952"><meta name="CHANGEDBY" content="Brian Confer"><meta name="CHANGED" content="20081102;343430"><style type="text/css"><!--
		@page { size: 8.5in 11in; margin: 0.79in }
		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }
	-->
	</style> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p><lj-cut text="Prologue"><p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">Liriel was not all that confident in his scribe abilities; not in the least considering the abruptness of his promotion. His complexion wasn't nearly as luminous as the other Celestials pouring into the great hall where the Elders held their august meetings. Fingers twitched nervously over the orb in his pocket, gliding along the smooth glass-like surface of the recording device. For an instant the young Celestial was blinded by the brightness of the great hall as he entered with the rest of the masses preparing for the council's arrival.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	The auspiciousness of the High Council wasn't the only thing that could make a young scribe nervous about the place. The ceiling extended into the heavens, or so it seemed, towering above the sleek, gleaming surface of the marble floors. Liriel could see his reflection in the large slabs and took a moment to tuck shimmering curls behind an ear. The room expanded on all sides and Liriel had a feeling he might be swallowed whole if he wasn't careful. Spectral light hung in the air like the stars that they hung in the expanse of the universe, reflecting down below on the ebony surface of the bench that ran in a wide U where the Elders would take their places soon.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	Liriel had always wanted to have been one of the elite who arranged the heavens, or perhaps even a Guide, but he took his job as a scribe seriously. He must have stalled while admiring the council hall because there was a very austere Celestial beckoning him sharply.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Come along, Liriel. You are not here to see the sites.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Y-yes, of course,&rdquo; was Liriel's timid reply. </font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	His guide led him to the second tier of benches set back from the first and offered a wave of his hand to indicate for Liriel to take a seat to his left. He had yet to be assigned to a council member but figured that the process was far less formal than he had at first imagined. </font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;You do know how to operate an orb, correct?&rdquo; His voice was smooth and calculated as it nudged against Liriel's thoughts. It had been a great while since any Celestial had a use for his vocal chords.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;I do. I didn't know using an orb was permitted in the High Council.&rdquo; Liriel mused between the two of them.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;They aren't. At least not by ordinary citizens. You have clearance to use yours. Do try and keep up.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	The Seraphim was not exaggerating. No sooner than Liriel retrieved the silvery orb from his pocket the head of the Elders began to speak. Liriel's hands worked furiously over the sparkling ball of energy floating just at his chest. Each finger dipped into the silvery threads weaving them to and fro in the undulating currents just beneath the orb's surface. Together the threads spelled out the thoughts of the Council with a specific focus on the member sitting just before him. </font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	The subject was changing from the opening agenda to a more pressing issue; if the tone of their collective thoughts were anything to go by.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Humanity has gone far enough. They have refused the idols. Some even talk of us as mere superstitions. Figments of their imaginations! We have lost all control.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Blasphemy to this extreme is unforgivable.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Force may be necessary.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	Liriel's fingers nearly tied themselves into knots, the pure force behind these thoughts were almost enough to send the small scribe toppling over backwards.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Please, High Council,&rdquo; Liriel perked as his assigned member spoke up, &ldquo;we knew this was a possibility since The Great War began. Lucifer's damage has been dealt, there is no escaping that. We should focus more on controlling this outbreak of freewill before it spreads any further.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;And what do you propose?&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Starting over, quite simply.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	A clamor rose up so forcefully in Liriel's mind that he nearly let the orb plummet to the floor. He only nearly managed to avoid a scene by catching the free falling sphere in one hand before replacing it. Dazed, his fingers only kept up with the flow of arguments from a lifetime of practice at the art of thought weaving. Finally clarity returned as the Elders reclaimed the discussion.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Humanity is still yet too young to be tossed aside. Yet--&rdquo; Liriel noted that the glossy robes and authoritative tone meant the speaker was at the head of the Elders. &ldquo;Yet we cannot deny the risk they pose to order. Let it be decided, then, that we should hold the keys to their destruction. If a time ever comes we will be prepared to deal with them then.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Would it not be too tempting for one of us to possess all of the keys and command power over both our plane and theirs?&rdquo; Liriel's eyes were trained on his superior as he spoke mentally to the entire council. &ldquo;Why do we not instead spread the keys about the Earth in only the locations parts of us know and parts of us do not; then not one of our number can wield that kind of power without the consent of the whole.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Adriel makes a sound point. We should also dictate on of our kind to reside among Humanity as a guardian and a herald for when the time has come to end them.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;A wise choice,&rdquo; Adriel didn't sound all that convinced, &ldquo;but who shall we send?&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Why not the one whose idea it was.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	Liriel sensed more than saw the tension in Adriel's being; and though he barely knew the Seraph he thought he detected a note of disdain in his projected thoughts.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Are you sure a Council member should be absent from his post for such a duration?&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;I'm sure your presence will be missed,&rdquo; the High Elder's tone seemed to indicate otherwise. &ldquo;It would be unwise to send anyone of a lower rank. The knowledge of the existence of these keys is not to leave this chamber.&rdquo;</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	Liriel could feel the tension almost as tangibly as he could feel the orb's threads wrapping around his fingers. The entire chamber stilled as the two Elders held a private mental argument. No orb would record these thoughts. Both of their eyes were aglow and locked together across the ebony bench. Liriel wasn't sure but he thought he could see their reflections flickering on its glossy surface. When it seemed the pair would continue this private debate indefinitely, the silence was broken by the High Council's de facto leader.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	&ldquo;Then it is settled. Adriel will oversee Humanity's progress from Earth and will not have access to the keys.&rdquo;	</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	The rest of the meeting was a blur of motion as Liriel's fingers rushed to keep up with the flurry of thoughts. None of the debates were anywhere near as heated nor as tense as the one Adriel had been a part of. The Seraph was conspicuously quiet for the remainder of the talks. When it was over, Adriel stalked from the chambers without a glance to Liriel.</font></font></p> <p style="margin-bottom: 0in;"><font face="Trebuchet MS, sans-serif"><font size="2">	It had been his first time as a scribe for a High Council member and now it looked as if it was also his last. </font></font></p></lj-cut><br /></meta></meta></meta></meta></meta></meta>
